             <tr> 
              <td height="10" width="20"> <img alt="spacer.gif" height="10" src="https://img.verticalresponse.com/email_layout/3257/spacer.gif" style="display: block; width: 20px; height: 10px;" width="20"></td> 
              <td align="left" style=" text-decoration: none; padding-left: 0; padding-top: 10px; padding-right: 0; padding-bottom: 10px;"> 
               <div style="margin: 0 0 0 0; color: #FFFFFF; line-height: 11px; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px"> 
                <a href="#" style="text-decoration: none; color: #ffffff;">Issue 2&nbsp;| August/September 2013</a>&nbsp;&nbsp;
               </div> </td> 
              <td align="right" style=" padding-left: 10px; padding-top: 10px; padding-right: 10px; padding-bottom: 10px;" width="200"> 
               <div style="margin: 0 0 0 0; color: #FFFFFF; line-height: 11px; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px"> 
                <a href="http://iris.edu" style="color: #FFFFFF; text-decoration: underline;">www.iris.edu</a>
               </div> </td> 
             </tr> 
            </tbody> 
           </table> </td> 
         </tr> 
         <tr> 
          <td align="center" valign="top" width="100%"> 
           <table align="center" border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="588"> 
            <tbody> 
             <tr> 
              <td align="left" style="padding-top: 0px; padding-left: 0px; padding-right: 40px; padding-bottom: 0px; line-height: 0px; text-align: left;" valign="top" width="418"> 
               <div style="margin: 0 0 10px 0; color: #1a1a1a; line-height: 24px; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size:24px"> 
                <br> Third OBSIP Cascadia Deployment Complete
               </div> 
               <div style="margin: 0 0 10px 0; color: #1a1a1a; line-height: 16px; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px">
                 63&nbsp;Instruments Will Stay&nbsp;on Seafloor 1 Year
               </div> 
               <div> 
                <img align="none" alt="Cascadia_2_newsletter" border="0" height="198" hspace="0" src="https://cc286088d6-custmedia.vresp.com/650ea523d0/Cascadia_2_newsletter.jpg" style="display: block; width: 371px; height: 198px;" title="Cascadia_2_newsletter" vspace="10" width="371">
               </div> 
               <div style="color: #474747; line-height: 15px; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 11px"> 
                <div style="margin: 0 0 10px 0"> 
                 <span style="font-size:8pt;"><span style="color: rgb(34, 34, 34); font-family: Arial, sans-serif;">The <a href="http://cascadia.uoregon.edu/CIET/">Cascadia Initiative</a> is an onshore/offshore seismic and geodetic experiment to better understand local earthquake generation, volcanic arc structure, and various aspects of the Cascadia Subduction Zone. This community experiment has relied on dialog and&nbsp;cooperation between the scientific community and local fishing agencies to minimize the impact on fishing operations while still achieving the scientific objectives.&nbsp;This summer, the&nbsp;<a href="http://www.obsip.org/">Ocean Bottom Seismograph Instrument Pool </a>(OBSIP) deployed 63&nbsp;<a href="http://www.obsip.org/experiments/experiment-list/2011/cascadia">ocean bottom seismometers</a> off the coast of the western United States as an extension of the&nbsp;onshore&nbsp;EarthScope Transportable Array. Instruments in the third Cascadia deployment will remain on the seafloor for one year, after which the instruments and data will be recovered. OBSIP plans to redeploy the instruments for a fourth year in the summer of 2014. Go to the <a href="http://cascadia.uoregon.edu/CIET/">Cascadia Initiative</a> page for more details on individual deployments.<br> &nbsp;</span></span>
                </div> 
               </div> <br> <br> 
               <div style="margin: 0 20px 10px 0; color: #1a1a1a; line-height: 24px; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 24px">
                 Middle America Site Characterization
               </div> 
               <div style="margin: 0 0 10px 0; color: #1a1a1a; line-height: 16px; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px">
                 Advanced Studies Institute&nbsp;Includes Data Acquisition
               </div> 
               <div> 
                <span style="display: none;">&nbsp;</span>
                <img align="none" alt="Ray_workshop_cropped" border="0" height="198" hspace="0" src="https://cc286088d6-custmedia.vresp.com/650ea523d0/Ray_workshop_cropped.jpg" style="display: block; width: 371px; height: 198px;" title="Ray_workshop_cropped" vspace="10" width="371"> 
                <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; line-height: 15px;"><span style="display: none;">&nbsp;</span><a href="http://www.iris.edu/hq/pasi_workshop">Bringing New Tools and Techniques to Bear on Earthquake Hazard Analysis and Mitigation</a>, partially funded by NSF's Pan American Advanced Studies Institute program, was designed for early career Earth scientists and earthquake engineers. Broad geographical involvement was important, and participants were drawn from more than a dozen countries throughout Central America, the Caribbean Sea region, and the United States. The curriculum was comprised of lectures and discussion, urban fieldwork using a variety of sensors and data acquisition systems, consultative computer analysis of the data that the participants collected, and presentation and comparison of hazard interpretations. The outcomes include deeper understanding and fostering of new research collaborations in earthquake hazard analysis, particularly site characterization techniques. Follow-up activities are being planned by the Alliance for Middle America Seismology (ALMAS). Please check the <a href="http://www.almas-online.org/">ALMAS website</a> soon for&nbsp;announcements.</span>
                <br> 
                <br> 
                <br> 
                <br> 
                <br> 
                <div style="margin: 0px 20px 10px 0px; color: rgb(26, 26, 26); line-height: 24px; font-size: 24px;"> 
                 <br> USArray Short Courses A Hit
                 <br> 
                 <div style="margin: 0 0 10px 0; color: #1a1a1a; line-height: 16px; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 16px">
                   Northwestern Hosts Over 50 Participants
                 </div> 
                 <div> 
                  <span style="display: none;">&nbsp;</span>
                  <img align="none" alt="Group-Intro_cropped 3" border="0" height="198" hspace="0" src="https://cc286088d6-custmedia.vresp.com/650ea523d0/Group-Intro_cropped%203.jpg" style="width: 371px; height: 198px;" title="Group-Intro_cropped 3" vspace="0" width="371">
                  <span style="color: rgb(0, 0, 0); font-family: Arial, sans-serif; font-size: 11px; line-height: 15px;"><span style="display: none;">&nbsp;</span>IRIS staff and several volunteers from the IRIS community organized two short courses for early career seismologists to teach them basic&nbsp;(Aug 6–9) and more advanced (Aug 12–16) techniques for obtaining, structuring, processing, and analyzing large data sets such as the USArray Transportable Array data holdings. The courses were hosted by Northwestern University, and balanced lecture, exercises, and student projects. These course assets will be compiled and made available on the <a href="http://www.iris.edu/hq/es_course_13/">short course web pages</a>, so stay tuned!</span>
                 </div> 
                </div> 
               </div> </td> 
              <td align="left" bgcolor="#cdde9f" style="padding: 15px 10px 10px; text-align: left;" valign="top" width="200"> 
               <div style="line-height: 13px; margin: 0px 0px 10px; font-family: Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; font-size: 12px;"> 
                <a href="http://www.iris.edu/hq/community"><b><span style="color: rgb(75, 0, 130);">Visit the IRIS Community Pages</span></b></a>
